Date: Fri 13 Jul 2012
Source: Robert Haddock <robhad@yahoo.com> [edited]


[re: ProMED-mail Salmonellosis - USA (02): (CA) nosocomial, neonatal 20120712.1199298]
----------------------------------------------------------------------
I have come to the conclusion that infants are exquisitely sensitive to small numbers of _Salmonella_ bacteria as in aerosol transmission via contaminated dust particles. We had a similar outbreak in our newborn nursery some years ago and I documented _Salmonella_ being tracked into the unit. A "sticky-mat" placed at the entrance to the unit seemed to solve the problem.

Haddock RL, SanNicolas A: Infant salmonellosis: vacuum cleaners used to investigate outbreak. J Environ Hlth 1989; 52(2): 106-7

Abstract
--------
Following 3 apparently unrelated cases of salmonellosis among newborn infants in a hospital nursery over a 5-month period, a specially modified vacuum cleaner was used to document the introduction of _Salmonella_ bacteria into the unit on footwear. This technique is proposed as an additional tool for the investigation of salmonellosis cases, particularly in instances when foodborne transmission cannot be incriminated as a source of infection.

--
Robert L. Haddock, DVM, MPH
Epidemiologist
<robhad@yahoo.com>

[ProMED-mail thanks Dr Haddock for his interesting comment regarding the neonatal, nosocomial salmonellosis cases. It is still unclear if the same strain caused both infections. - Mod.LL]
